node.text: Now with English subtitles! Yoel, a recent immigrant from Cuba (only 4 months in this country) finally is able to express what has been frustrating him for 36 years and the recent developments in Cuba.  Unfortunately, we still cannot say he can express this freely because we risk our seeing our families, our families lives, and the possibility of entering/leaving cuba because of the regimes control even outside the island.  But Yoel finally after 36 years can no longer take other people talking in front of him.  This is what he says about the embargo, oppression and life in cuba today.

node.title: English! A message from a recent Cuban immigrant

node.text:
The nightmare continues! Another sad day for Cuba in its battle for basic human rights like the freedom of speech.  Decree 35 now limits Cubans speech on the internet and effectively makes the state the only arbiter of what is “against the prestige”. Whatever the F that means. 

Remember in cuba, the entire system from top to bottom is owned by the state. The press, the communication provider, the internet, the judicial system, the “Congress”. All of it is controlled and run by one party. One choice. One government.

I make these in English to continue the conversation for all of us in the diaspora who might have lost the language and the world so they can too can keep up with what is happening.  Yes I know I spelt decreto wrong accidentally. Pinga. I did this so fast LOL. 

If not today mi gente, tomorrow cuba will be free. The government, in this act of desperation, already lost. 

#cuba #noaldecretoley35 #patriayvida

node.accessibility_caption: Another sad day for human rights in cuba
The Cuban government implemented decree 35
What is it? A law defining cyber terrorism and making the state the only arbiter of what goes against the “prestige of the state”
So what? This means Cubans are restricted to what they can put on the internet. They are subjected to fines or sanctions.
But there is hope (sunflowers growing)
Sunflower grown.  Why would they make a law if the threat wasn’t that big?
None of this has to do with the embargo
Follow Twitter cuba for more!

node.text:
This is one of many UNACCEPTABLE stories of human rights abuses that have happened during the 11-July protests in Cuba.  For Manolo manguera and over 550 people, protesting peacefully landed them in jail without the right to a fair trail and without the right of fair representation.  In less than 3 weeks, hundred have been convicted of crimes and sent to maximum security prisons where they are treated horribly by Cuban officials. Their official crime is labeled under “spreading COVID-19” of which no pro-government protestors were arrested of when they showed their patriotism to the revolution in the days following. THESE are the injustices the Regime will never admit to. All of us in tje international community who have been protesting and waving our Cuban flags have the obligation to now pressure the cuban government in releasing ALL POLITICAL PRISONERS. 

History has showed that international pressure has prevented the Cuban government from arresting famous dissidents.  It’s up to us to make the infamous, famous. 
 
Please we are begging you to share their stories.

node.text: Now with English subtitles! Yoel, a recent immigrant from Cuba (only 4 months in this country) finally is able to express what has been frustrating him for 36 years and the recent developments in Cuba.  Unfortunately, we still cannot say he can express this freely because we risk our seeing our families, our families lives, and the possibility of entering/leaving cuba because of the regimes control even outside the island.  But Yoel finally after 36 years can no longer take other people talking in front of him.  This is what he says about the embargo, oppression and life in cuba today.

EXPLAINED: The cuban economy is very complex and blaming the downfall on the embargo lacks serious perspective in the many other factors that cause economies to collapse. Here are just some examples of internal domestic policies the Cuban government has implemented that don’t help in the situation. In fact, the inefficiencies are so well known that it is very common for Cubans to mention (quietly) the two embargos. But the workers of America won’t know that..... because they don’t ever actually talk to Cubans. They only speak over us. 

Design again by @juliettehelen. 

#soscuba #cuba #cubanembargo #handsoffcuba #abajoelbloqueo #endtheembargo #abajoladictadura #vivacubalibre #diazcanelsingao

May be an image of text that says '#SOSCUBA Cuban Economy is Complex Like all economies, Cuba's is a complex web dictated by policies the Cuban government has created. The US embargo isn't the only thing Ûhing directly affecting the suffering of the Cuban people. The dictatorship heavily participates. Here are some examples @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#SOSCUBA Acopio A state-run agricultural distribution agency. Farmers are mandated to sell a certain quota to the state (Acopio) and are disincentivized to create surplus because of the limited amount of crops that can be sold directly to consumers. Acopio sets prices and pays farmers in Cuban pesos, not hard currency. Frequently, they fail to pick up crops on time and over 25% of production is left to rot. This program directly affects the number of available crops on the market contributes the scarcity of basic staple items grown naturally on the island. @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of tree, outdoors and text that says '#SOSCUBA Monetary Policy Introduction to dual currencies Most Cubans are paid in a worthless currency: Cuban pesos. However, most food items in markets with any surplus are sold in hard currency. The dual monetary policy has created an economic disparity between Cubans who have access to money outside the island, and those who do not. @mimaincuba ejuliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '#SOSCUBA Lack of Economic Liberties Cubans cannot just open any business. They are limited to certain licenses the government provides. Most allowed businesses are "low-skilled meaning services like restaurants, barbershops, spas etc. Businesses that scale or integrate essential parts of the economy are not allowed and are directly controlled by the state, one giant corporation. @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.
